metadata.name: RAUSCH #138
metadata.description:
RAUSCH is a series of generative artworks that explore imaginary digital architectures. 

This series challenges traditional notions of architectural representation and raises important questions about the role of resolution in design. Just as the pixel resolution of an image affects its perceived quality, the resolution of an architectural space can affect its qualities and livability. By embracing digital variation through codes, this series explores the interplay between abstract and concrete space through multiple resolutions. 

RAUSCH is inspired by the feeling of being overwhelmed by complex, chaotic and messy sensations, and aims to engage the viewer through a sense of wonder, disorientation, and awe.

Released on the occasion of Companions of Code, a group exhibition by VerticalCrypto Art at The NFT Gallery in London. 
Curated by Micol Ap. Exhibition 10-24 February 2023 

___________________________________________________
RAUSCH Controls:

Animation: 
‚Ä¢ ‚Äò1 - 2 - 3 - 4‚Äô animate views
‚Ä¢ 'MouseClick' pause/play animation

Functions:
(press key & wait)
‚Ä¢ 'F' 24 FPS
‚Ä¢ 'B' b/w mode 

Resize Canvas:
(press key & wait)
‚Ä¢ '6' Portrait A4 - 1000x1414
‚Ä¢ '7' Landscape 16:9 - 1920x1080
‚Ä¢ '8' Portrait 9:16 - 1080x1920
‚Ä¢ '9' Square 1:1 - 1024x1024
‚Ä¢ 'DoubleClick' Fullscreen

Save & Export Image:
‚Ä¢ 'S' save a .png of in current resolution

Save & Export GIF:
‚Ä¢ 'G' save a 1-2 sec. seamless loop .gif of current view 
‚Ä¢ 'P' save a 12-24 sec. seamless loop .gif of all the views
‚Ä¢ 'T‚Äô scale down current resolution, save a 12 sec. seamless loop .gif

Steps to save a gif/png :
‚Ä¢ go in live/open mode (wait)
‚Ä¢ resize canvas with 6,7,8, or 9 to your desired aspect ratio (wait)
‚Ä¢ press S,G or P to save & download (wait) 
‚Ä¢ enjoy RAUSCH :)

Save & Export GIF for social media sharing:
‚Ä¢ go in live/open mode (wait)
‚Ä¢ press T or G wait for recalculation & download. 
‚Ä¢ enjoy RAUSCH 
‚Ä¢ post on Twitter ;)

This token may not work on mobile(!), but it allows exporting .png and .gif (see controls) to enjoy RAUSCH on different displays or mobile. Tested on Mozilla, Chrome, Safari. Created with P5js & p5.createLoop

metadata.name: Richter #305
metadata.description:
Richter is the second collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog, following their first project called Gerhard. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time.
 
Richter works with data from 4 of 24 highres images, 30mb in total. This is the maximum size fxhash allows for a project and three times more than Gerhard. Richard Nadler created stunning new textures, enabling more variation in composition and detail to emerge at much higher resolution. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Richter elevates the approach from Gerhard with new methods for the realtime rendering process and new features like offline-first caching. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels as data.
 
Richter is featured in the exhibition "Generative Abstraction" at Expanded.art in Berlin.
 
- Click to start a new layer of motion and color.
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen.
- Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save the canvas.
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

metadata.name: Through the Lens of the Sixties #6
metadata.description:
These colors symbolize hot summers in the sixties, crowded beaches, socializing of young people. They also symbolize psychedelic drugs that became very popular in the sixties. The color palette in this work is characteristic of Polaroids, which were very popular at the time, and a lot of them oversaturated every photo.

The irregular shapes we see on each iteration symbolize the young people who led the cultural revolution. They symbolize dance movements without rules. They symbolize Jimi, Janis and Woodstock. Although the shapes are without strict rules, somehow they fit together perfectly.

Coded in p5.js

Big shoutout to Steve Makerspace who was a huge inspiration and Irit Yablon who saved me when things went wrong.

Bajiru, July, 2022.

metadata.name: Self, Superego #12
metadata.description:
The second installment of the Self trilogy.

Superego is defined as: the one of the three divisions of the psyche in psychoanalytic theory that is only partly conscious, represents internalization of parental conscience and the rules of society, and functions to reward and punish through a system of moral attitudes, conscience, and a sense of guilt.

Please see attached fx(text) article or go to https://ty-vek.art/self-trilogy for more on concept/mechanics/etc. It‚Äôs a bit of long read, but worth it.

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

All projects are written in vanilla Javascript, composed as SVG and then rendered to a 2d canvas.

There might be slight differences in rendering from browser to browser. This is expected as they might translate the SVG slightly differently. Let's call Chromium renderings canonical. They also render faster there and we love that.

Press "S" to save a PNG.
Press "V" to save a SVG. (Chromium browsers render these pretty well.)

By default, these will render at 2400 x 3200 pixels. This is at density 1.

To render at a larger resolution you can append ‚Äú&d=2‚Äù to the end of the url. This will double the resolution. You can also use 3 or 4 or whatever your browser can handle. Safari tends to have problems with this, so stick with Chromium based browsers (Chrome, Edge, Brave, etc.)

If you want to render as a square image, so it is optimized for ummm.. your pfp or something, you can append ‚Äú&sq=t‚Äù to the url.

If you want to get rid of grain, just append ‚Äú&g=n‚Äù

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

https://ty-vek.art/self-trilogy
https://twitter.com/ty__vek
https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/Ty%20Vek/articles

metadata.name: Blotto! #81
metadata.description:
Vanilla JS + SVG
November 2022

Edition of 365

The starting point for this piece was an attempt to simulate the effect of dropping coloured inks or paints onto wet or dry paper ("blots") by combining mixed gradients and various levels of svg filters. I then added stroke and fine line drawings to the blots and played around with rotation and opacity and leaving blanks in the grids. 

The results range from minimal smooth circles, sometimes fading away into the background, to noisy splashes or clouds.

The defined features of the project are:

Blot palettes: 9+n (1 is generated randomly)
Blotting paper: 6 colours
Blot grid: 5 layouts (1x1, 3x3, 5x5, 10x10, 20x20)
Blot stroke: true/false
Blot blanks: true/false
Blotted lines: true/false
Blotulence! (extra turbulence): true/false

To save a PNG file, press "P" or save an SVG by pressing "S"

This project has been tested and works in Chrome, Brave, Edge and Firefox (a little slower on the latter, so please be patient). It does not work in Safari or on IOS at this time.

// PRIMARY SALES
If/when the project mints out, 50% of primary will be donated to Girls Who Code Canada (https://girlswhocode.com/en-ca) and the other 50% to Breakfast Club Canada and I will post the donation receipts on the fx(hash) Discord as well as on my Twitter & genart.social.
